First, we can simplify the given equation by noticing that $\sum_{i=1}^{216} a_i x_i = \frac{107}{215}$.

To do this, let $S$ be the sum of all terms on the right-hand side. Then,

\begin{align*}
S &= \dfrac{107}{215} + \sum_{i=1}^{216} \dfrac{a_i x_i^2}{2(1-a_i)} \\
&= \dfrac{107}{215} + \sum_{i=1}^{216} a_i x_i - 2\sum_{i=1}^{216} \dfrac{a_i x_i^2}{2(1-a_i)}.
\end{align*}

Now, we can use the fact that $\sum_{i=1}^{216} a_i = \frac{107}{215}$ to simplify $S$ further:

\begin{align*}
S &= \dfrac{107}{215} + \left(\frac{107}{215}\right) - 2\sum_{i=1}^{216} \dfrac{a_i x_i^2}{2(1-a_i)} \\
&= \frac{214}{215} - 2\sum_{i=1}^{216} \dfrac{a_i x_i^2}{2(1-a_i)}.
\end{align*}

Since $\sum_{i=1}^{216} a_i = \frac{107}{215}$, we know that $S$ is equal to the sum of all terms on the right-hand side.

